    "narrative": "The daily efficiency scores for April 30th reveal a compressed field, with our most reliable contributors hovering just below the \"Strong\" 60-point threshold. **Corbin Carroll** leads the pack with a 59.06 rating; while he faces a formidable arm in Woodruff (xERA 2.90), his elite sprint speed remains our primary engine in a 5x5 format where stolen bases are at a premium. The decision to keep **Corbin Carroll** active is bolstered by a +4% bump for Woodruff\u2019s slow delivery, which historically invites high-volume theft opportunities. **Brice Turang** (58.33) mirrors this strategic focus, benefiting from a favorable #2 lineup spot and a manageable matchup against Soroka, making him a cornerstone of our daily efficiency goals.\n\nWhile our bench remains largely stagnant due to off-days for **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Josh Naylor**, the most difficult exclusion was **Mickey Moniak**. Although his underlying metrics against left-handed pitching have shown volatility, his ability to capitalize on the +5% wind-out factor and favorable SP xERA (4.20) nearly earned him a spot. Ultimately, the optimizer prioritized the consistent order-based value of **Kyle Karros** (56.32), whose platoon advantage against Abbott provides a more stable floor than **Mickey Moniak**'s speculative upside. **James Wood** and **Austin Riley** round out the active starters; **James Wood**\u2019s +10% order bonus effectively offsets the risk of facing Peralta, while **Austin Riley** remains a lock despite the tough assignment against Valdez, purely for his durability and consistent contribution across R/RBI categories.",
